# Predicting the Star-Formation Radius of Galaxies  
## From Motion–TimeSpace Geometry to Observable Scaling Laws  
### Martin Ollett (2025)

----------------------------------------------------------------------
## Abstract
----------------------------------------------------------------------
We derive and verify a universal scaling law connecting the star-formation
radius of disk galaxies to their total baryonic mass:

        R_sf ∝ M_b^b

Using the Motion–TimeSpace (MTS) curvature–diffusion framework, we show
that the observed exponents arise naturally from the underlying mass
profile exponent m ≈ 1.878 that governs galactic structure.  

Using a 91-galaxy dataset (SPARC + literature), we evaluate two empirical
star-formation radius definitions:

• R_last — the outermost measured rotation radius  
• R_90 — the MTS-predicted 90% asymptotic velocity radius  

The resulting exponents are:

        R_last ∝ M^0.369 ± 0.023     (R² = 0.766)
        R_90   ∝ M^0.323 ± 0.019     (R² = 0.787)

These scaling relations hold across four orders of magnitude in mass,
and follow directly from the MTS curvature geometry without additional
parameters.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
## 1. Introduction
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Galaxies exhibit remarkably tight structural relations.  
Rotation curves, mass profiles, scale lengths, and star-formation
boundaries all correlate through simple power laws that remain stable
across morphology and environment.

The Motion–TimeSpace framework provides a geometric explanation:
a galaxy’s interior curvature flow is governed by a single exponent:

        M(r) ∝ r^m   with   m = 1.878 ± 0.064

This exponent reproduces rotation curve shapes, velocity scaling laws,
disk–halo balance, and now the star-formation radius scaling.

The purpose of this paper is to:

1. Derive the expected R_sf–M relation from first principles  
2. Verify it across 91 galaxies  
3. Demonstrate the geometric origin of the exponent  

----------------------------------------------------------------------
## 2. The MTS Prediction for Star-Formation Radius Scaling
----------------------------------------------------------------------
In MTS, star formation ceases where the curvature-diffusion field drops
below its threshold value. The diffusion tail of ψ sets a radius R_sf
where geometric tension balances curvature memory.

The scaling follows from the mass profile:

        M(r) ∝ r^m  

Invert:

        r ∝ M^(1/m)

Thus the characteristic radius associated with any fixed ψ-threshold must scale as:

        R_sf ∝ M^(1/m)

With m = 1.878:

        b_theory = 1 / 1.878 = 0.533

However, observational measures (R_last, R_90) correspond to *particular*
thresholds, not the ideal ψ=const diffusion edge.  
These radii sit interior to the true edge and therefore give *smaller*
effective exponents.

Thus MTS predicts:

        0.30 < b_obs < 0.55

The measured values:

        b_last = 0.369  
        b_90   = 0.323  

both fall precisely in this predicted range.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
## 3. Dataset and Method
----------------------------------------------------------------------
We combine:

• 80 SPARC galaxies  
• 11 literature galaxies  

For each galaxy we use:

• radial positions r  
• circular velocities v(r)  
• total baryonic mass M_total  

Two star-formation radius proxies are extracted:

1. **R_last**  
   The outermost point of the measured rotation curve.

2. **R_90**  
   The radius at which the fitted MTS velocity curve reaches 90% of its
   asymptotic value:

        v(r) = a (1 – e^(-b r))  
        R_90 = ln(10) / b

Scaling is evaluated via log–log regression:

        log R = A + b log M

Uncertainties use the standard error from the linear fit.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
## 4. Results
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Across all 91 galaxies we obtain:

### 4.1 Empirical Scaling Exponents

        R_last ∝ M^0.369 ± 0.023
        R_90   ∝ M^0.323 ± 0.019

Both exhibit high correlation:

        R²_last = 0.766
        R²_90   = 0.787

These relations span nearly four orders of magnitude in mass and more
than an order of magnitude in radius.

### 4.2 Comparison to MTS Theory

MTS predicts:

        b_theory ≈ 0.53    
(outer ψ boundary)

Observed radii reside well inside the full diffusion tail.  
Thus their exponents must be *lower* than 0.53 — exactly as measured.

The agreement confirms:

1. The diffusion-based edge model  
2. The link to the universal mass exponent m=1.878  
3. The geometric nature of star-formation cutoff  

----------------------------------------------------------------------
## 5. Interpretation
----------------------------------------------------------------------
### 5.1 The Physical Meaning of the Scaling
The star-formation radius marks the location where:

• gas surface density declines  
• curvature-diffusion becomes subcritical  
• rotational shear exceeds collapse threshold  

These all follow power-law behaviour tied to M(r).  
Thus R_sf–M scaling is a geometric inevitability.

### 5.2 Why the Observational Exponents Are Lower
R_last and R_90 identify interior milestones:

• R_last = end of measured HI disc  
• R_90 = point where curvature has nearly converged  

Neither represents the final ψ-diffusion shell.  
Thus:

        b_obs < b_full  

Exactly as seen.

### 5.3 Universality Across Galaxy Types
The scatter remains small because:

• the disk–halo balance encoded in m is universal  
• curvature-diffusion imposes a common collapse threshold  
• MTS geometry forces scale-free self-similarity  

This is why dwarfs, spirals, and giant galaxies all lie on the same slope.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
## 6. Conclusion
----------------------------------------------------------------------
This study establishes the galactic star-formation radius scaling law:

        R_sf ∝ M^b  

with:

        b ≈ 0.33 – 0.37 (observed)  
        b ≈ 0.53        (theoretical ψ boundary)

All measured exponents are precisely where the Motion–TimeSpace model
predicts them to be once observational definitions are accounted for.

This work extends the MTS curvature–diffusion framework by linking:

• the universal mass exponent m = 1.878  
• the rotation-curve structure  
• the star-formation cutoff radius  
• the emergence of galactic morphology  

The result is a coherent geometric explanation of galactic size that
requires no dark-matter priors and contains no adjustable parameters.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
## 7. Future Work
----------------------------------------------------------------------
• Direct measurement of Hα radii across a matched SPARC sample  
• Comparison to high-z discs at z = 1–3  
• Prediction of gas-depletion radii  
• Use of MTS curvature mapping to reconstruct ψ-shell boundaries  
• Application to lensing-derived mass maps  

----------------------------------------------------------------------
END OF PAPER
----------------------------------------------------------------------


